      <h4><div>Anne Manson conducts cellist<br>Ariel Barnes</div></h4>
      <p>This is a late programme change, but change is good! Ariel Barnes, principal cellist of the Vancouver Symphony Orchestra, has been described as creating a &rdquo;mesmerizing musical experience&ldquo; by combining his &rdquo;deep personal connection&rdquo; (<i>Toronto Live Music Report</i>), with a &ldquo;luscious tone and technical prowess&rdquo; (<i>The Vancouver Sun</i>).</p>
      <p>Barnes was recently selected as one of six cellists across the nation to celebrate the launch of <a href="http://music.cbc.ca/"><b>cbcmusic.ca</b></a> as a featured artist in the Canadian Bach Cello Suite Project and in 2012, was winner of the 2012 Canada Council Instrument Bank Competition. He has been awarded the use of the 1730 Newland Joannes Franciscus Celoniatus cello, built in Turin, Italy.</p>
      <p>Ariel Barnes is passionate about the chamber music literature, and for this concert will perform Haydn's D major cello concerto.</p>
      <p>Also, at this concert Anne Manson presents the first of two works by Leo&#353; Jan&aacute;&#269;ek.</p>
      <p><b>Programming change</b></p>
      <p>The originally-programmed performance and debut of Manitoba composer Heidi Ouellette&rsquo;s <i>Life on Mars</i> has been postponed. In its place, we will present <i>Divertissement</i>, for string quartet and string orchestra, by Canadian composer Pierre Mercure. MCO has performed this work on two occasions, but not since 1988!</p>

